title: Delta Wedding
author: Welty, Eudora
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I knew within the first few pages that I would love this book, and I definitely did. The writing-wow! This is my first Eudora Welty and her storytelliI knew within the first few pages that I would love this book, and I definitely did. The writing-wow! This is my first Eudora Welty and her storytelling is like none other. Written in the 1940s and set in the 1920s, the story tells about a week in the life of a Southern family living on the Mississippi Delta. Nothing special happens, it’s just life. But what a week it was for the Fairchilds. For a more modern perspective, imagine the chaos in the opening scenes of Home Alone (all the commotion and the various branches of the family tree all under one roof) plus the dysFUNctional dynamics in The Family Stone. That is the first 6 chapters of this book (there are only 7 chapters). The reader is inserted in the madness of a family wedding and gets to experience all of the highs and lows along the way. But Welty has this amazing ability to completely change the tone and pace once the wedding is over. I can’t say enough good things! I will note I appreciated the introduction by Anne Tyler. She gives the 21st century some things to think about when examining this type of literature. My 2023 reading project is to read the works of American female authors from the 20th century-the ones I have mostly overlooked. I am so glad I started with Ms Welty. ...more

author: Strout, Elizabeth*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Simply wonderful. I knew in the opening pages that this book would transport me back to those early days of the pandemic. While that doesn’t sound likSimply wonderful. I knew in the opening pages that this book would transport me back to those early days of the pandemic. While that doesn’t sound like a pleasant walk down memory lane, I felt strangely peaceful. She captures these uncertain days with such depth and emotion, not forgetting anything: i.e toilet paper shortages and leggings as pants. She takes the reader through the racial injustice reckoning we watched that summer as well as the 2020 election and the insurrection and patiently invites us to lay down our biases. We see a wonderful mother, healing from her own wounds of childhood and striving to giver her adult children the mother she never had. We see grief over the loss of her second husband and navigating life in lockdown with her first husband! All of this in just 288 pages! I read it in basically two sittings and I highly recommend you do the same. I have read just one other book in the Lucy Barton series, but you don’t need to have read any of them to enjoy this one. ...more

review: 3.5 stars. When I read memoir I try not to rate based on the author’s story and more about the crafting of the book. I enjoyed this book, I listened t3.5 stars. When I read memoir I try not to rate based on the author’s story and more about the crafting of the book. I enjoyed this book, I listened to it (my favorite was to consume memoir) and found myself laughing and crying at various times. I felt some more editing was needed as some chapters ended on strange notes (example, one chapter ended with the exclamation “Jesus!”, it made sense on audio but I don’t think it would have in print) and some chapters could have been shorter. And why 99 chapters? I was hoping there would be a surprise 100, that would have felt more resolved, haha. As for the “tea” she spills, I felt some of it was enlightening and some felt a little petty. She critiques herself and her own actions in addition to many (many) others. I have some opinions on the Matt Laurer scandal, but I’ll save that for a conversation if anyone is interested :)One thing that bothered me was her continued mentioning of her body. It seems that she still struggles with her body image and I just wish she could use her voice to promote more body positivity. review: The Sentence was my first Louise Erdrich book and I am happy to say it will be the first of many. There is nothing better than discovering love for a The Sentence was my first Louise Erdrich book and I am happy to say it will be the first of many. There is nothing better than discovering love for a writer with an exceptional catalog! The Sentence is the pandemic book everyone needs to read. It covers those traumatic first days of March 2020 and goes deeper into the race relations exposed that summer, starting with the murder of George Floyd. The book takes place in Minneapolis, so it felt real and raw. The author doesn’t tell the reader what or how to think but challenges the reader to open up one’s mind to others’ experiences. I dog eared so many pages that I’ll have to buy my own copy to mark it up. I particularly loved the main character and her husband, it is rare to have a solid married couple throughout a book. The side characters were fun and the ghost story was the thread that brought the entire book together to form a beautiful tapestry about trauma, love, and family. I highly recommend. ...more

The Younger Wife is told in the addicting plot style where a “big event” happens in the first pages and the rest of the book tells the story of the events leading up to it, along with some flashes of the big event told by another narrator. Each chapter ended with a little cliffhanger which made it hard to put down. I flew through the second half in one sitting. This follows the same pattern as her other recent books as far as suspense and family life mixed with enough wit and humor to balance out a potentially heavy topic. I didn’t love all the characters and didn’t love everything about the plot, but it certainly delivers an exciting reading experience. If you loved The Jane Austen Society, you will love this follow up!I was lucky to get an advanced copy of this book from the publisher via NetGalley. If you loved The Jane Austen Society, you will love this follow up! Evie Stone from the society leaves small town life and emerges in London after studying at Cambridge. She pursues a job at Bloomsbury Books where she meets a cast of characters that rivals the society members. We are introduced to the shop girls-Vivien and Grace as well as the surly manager, Mr. Dutton, whose medical condition requires him to leave the shop, and the women get a chance to lead. In constant competition with the men in the shop, the ladies use their skills and smarts to increase revenue and improve upon Mr. Dutton’s famous “rules.” Each chapter opens with one of his rules and promptly expands on how that rule was broken by an employee. With lots of excitement and even some subterfuge, we are immersed in the story of these women and their quest to outsmart the men once and for all. title: The Only Plane in the Sky: An Oral History of 9/11
author: Graff, Garrett M.*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I set out to read/listen to this leading up to 9/11/21, the 20th anniversary of the day that changed America. This book is truly a gift to the world. I set out to read/listen to this leading up to 9/11/21, the 20th anniversary of the day that changed America. This book is truly a gift to the world. The author took on a tremendous task of telling the story of those who experienced first hand the horrors of that day. I will remember many parts of this book, but the one that sticks with me is Genelle Guzman, the final survivor of the Twin Towers. She was rescued after 27 hours of being essentially buried alive. She said she prayed for 27 hours straight and she changed her life after experiencing the presence of the Holy Spirit that day. I love books that bring God into the world and her story underscored an already beautiful yet tragic account of senseless tragedy. This really should be required listening for all Americans, if not all humans. It is well worth the time spent. I am forever grateful to the brave rescue workers who sacrificed everything that day. Their story will live on through these survivors and through all who will bear witness to their story. May we never again face a day like 9/11/01. And yet may we also come together again as a nation as we did in the days after. Lord, in your mercy, hear our prayer. ...more

review: 5 stars for Remember by Lisa Genova. I have been a fan of Genova’s work ever since I picked up Still Alice at a used book sale in a beach town where I5 stars for Remember by Lisa Genova. I have been a fan of Genova’s work ever since I picked up Still Alice at a used book sale in a beach town where I used to live. Is this an oddly specific memory? Do I remember the place I bought every book I own? No, I just encoded it with extra information like the book sale and the beach town, so my brain was more likely to remember it. Remember teaches us how the brain stores memory, how we retrieve those memories, and how we forget those memories. We learn how Alzheimer’s works and how it’s different than “normal” forgetting and memory decline. And we learn how to prevent Alzheimer’s (spoiler-get some sleep!). All in all, this book is an easily digestible manual for all things memory. If you are a fan of Genova’s books, you will appreciate her light hearted way of handling serious subjects. It felt so personal, like I was reading emails from a friend. The only criticism I had was that it left me wanting more in most chapters! But not really, becCheck out other s at my blog www.everydaymamabooks.comOh my. I can't lie. This one made me want to throw it across the room. But not really, because it was on my Kindle and I love my Kindle way too much to hurt it. Book 2 dives into the life of the now Queen Beatrice. Both books are told in the voice of four different characters, which felt a little too much, especially in Book 2. We have Beatrice, sister Samantha, Samantha’s friend Nina, and the foil-Daphne Deighton. Each one of these young ladies has a love interest in Book 1 and then they swap partners in Book 2, as if they are at a square dance rather than a palace. Basically, the theme of Majesty is “love the one you’re with.” It felt so immature and downright frustrating at times. Daphne, in particular, drove me crazy and I felt the author really missed some opportunities with this character. In fact, the word “comeuppance” came to mind many times while reading, but evidently never crossed the author’s mind while writing. My biggest beef-and fair warning, this is a rant coming on-was ALL THE DRINKING! Oh my, these kids drank all.the.time. If a bad decision needed to be made, you can bet there was alcohol (or Daphne) involved. In this version of America, the drinking age is 18, which is pointed out in both books, I guess to make sure it is clear they were “legal.” But why do this? It felt like sloppy writing, not to mention, horrible to feature so prominently in a YA book. While the author made sure to include LGBTQ characters and some discussion around racism and interracial relationships, she certainly didn’t see a problem with drunken decision making. I can't recommend this one. ...more

In the particularly vitriolic environment that has characterized America in 2020, this book teaches us how to say the two most powerful words in our language: “I’m sorry.” We learn the gift it gives the hurt party as well as the apologizer itself. review: This book was given to me via NetGalley and BQB publishing in exchange for my honest .Give tells the story of a family. And not just a typical fThis book was given to me via NetGalley and BQB publishing in exchange for my honest .Give tells the story of a family. And not just a typical family. Len and Laurel begin the narration as the new parents of Jessie. Their marriage has been rocky since day one and they are on the verge of separating when Laurel learns she is pregnant with Emma. Emma comes along but the marriage doesn’t. All Len wants is his daughters and he is surprised Laurel gives them to him without a fight. The story goes on from there switching in the voices of Laurel and Len and eventually Jessie and Emma. Len’s second wife also narrates as well. The book covers 20+ years and the drama is heavy throughout. Laurel never quite figures out motherhood and Jessie and Emma struggle with love and family in their own ways. The novel attempts to answer the questions of what does a mother look like? How much does biology really matter? And can you really ever love your children enough?This was a debut novel and while it was very well written and captivating, I didn’t love it. I had a hard time connecting with any of the characters. I found myself reading quickly to find out what happened and to be able to move on from that person’s narration. The author did really hit the nail on the head with the scenes of what having 2 babies is like though! I felt my heart racing thinking of those early days for myself with my two girls. I appreciated the raw reality she gave of this stage. As I said the writing was excellent and quite addicting! I look forward to more novels by this author....more

title: The Paris Library
author: Charles, Janet Skeslien*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Odile is a young lady who is a Parisian city girl. She grew up comfortably with her parents and twin brother. She is a young adult now and is ready toOdile is a young lady who is a Parisian city girl. She grew up comfortably with her parents and twin brother. She is a young adult now and is ready to take on some adventure in her life, especially adventure surrounded by books. She always loved The American Library in Paris so it felt like a natural first job for her. She categorizes books in her mind according to the Dewey Decimal System and she can think of a book quote for just about any circumstance. She meets wonderful “habitues” or subscribers that frequent the library daily. She is living her dream! Before long, Paris becomes occupied by Nazi forces and life begins to change. Odile navigates falling in love, missing her brother who has gone to war, dealing with work and friend stress, and has to face harsh truths about her own father. She learns that the decisions she has made have far reaching impact and suddenly her world becomes very small. Through it all, she turns to literature for comfort and assurance that the light will endure. Odile’s journey takes her to the United States and picks up 40 year later when she meets a neighbor girl, Lily. Lily narrates every few chapters as the scene goes back and forth between Froid, Montana and Paris. Lily and Odile strike up a beautiful friendship right when they need each other the most. Throughout the book, other characters barrage several chapters as we see the story from another perspective. Overall, I loved this book. Historical fiction is one of my favorite genres. I especially loved the references to other books. I have come to learn that authors who are able to write books about books have a special gift and this one is no exception. I found myself highlighting the books that are referenced so I can add them to my to read list. I really enjoyed reading about the American Library in Paris and learning about the heroics of libraries during WWII. I never thought about the need to evacuate books! I wasn’t a huge fan of the Montana story line but I understand the connection. I just wanted more of Paris! I recommend this book for anyone who loves historical fiction and books about books! Thank you to Net Galley and the publisher for this advanced copy in exchange for my ....more

title: The Wife Upstairs
author: Hawkins, Rachel*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Disclaimer: If you have never read Jane Eyre by Charlotte Bronte, then you may enjoy this book as a suspenseful, exciting story. However, if you know Disclaimer: If you have never read Jane Eyre by Charlotte Bronte, then you may enjoy this book as a suspenseful, exciting story. However, if you know and love (or even just know) Jane Eyre, then you may get a little upset with this one. Read on.Jane is a young woman with a troubled past. She grew up in the foster care system and had a rough experience being passed around from house to house and group home to group home. She reinvents herself and even takes on a new name and leaves her old life behind. After some false starts, she finds herself in Alabama and takes on a job as dog walker in a posh neighborhood-Thornfield Estates. Soon she meets Eddie Rochester who adopts a dog, Adele (are you catching on yet?!) and she begins to work for Eddie. They begin to fall for each other and things move rather quickly towards engagement. Eddie is a widower whose wife, Bea (short for Bertha, but you already knew that) was thought to have died in a boating accident. While some folks are surprised Eddie moved on so quickly after Bea’s death, Jane is happy to take her place. The catch comes when the narration shifts to Bea’s voice and we learn that she is not in fact dead, she is actually hidden in Eddie’s house in a special panic room. Just when Jane thinks she has shed her traumatic past, she finds herself walking right into a new, even harsher reality. Will she learn the truth about Bea? Is she really safe in Eddie’s arms? The reader is taken on an adventure of many twists, turns, and dives in The Wife Upstairs.I have to admit, I am struggling with this one. I have read Jane Eyre twice, once in high school and once in my early 30s. I read it differently at those two unique periods in my life. I am a Mr. Rochester fan, I just am. And I’m not even sorry. But Eddie? Just not the same. At all. I enjoyed the pacing and suspense in this book, but I am afraid Charlotte Bronte may be turning in her grave. While there are many character names that are exact references from Jane Eyre, and Jane herself has a traumatic past separated from her family, the similarities grow thin the more the story evolves. The twist takes it very far away from Jane Eyre, to the point the comparison completely dies. I also wish it had a few less f-bombs, which I find tacky. Especially taking a famous quote like, “Reader, I married him” and changing it to something far less savory (I’ll leave this to your imagination). In short, I don’t recommend, unless you are not invested in Jane Eyre and don’t mind the f word.Regardless, I am thankful to NetGalley and the publisher for the advanced copy in exchange for my honest ....more

review: Cady is a college freshman who has been accepted to her dream school: Harvard University. She is living her dream! But it all feels wrong because her Cady is a college freshman who has been accepted to her dream school: Harvard University. She is living her dream! But it all feels wrong because her brother isn't there to share it with her. Eric died by suicide just a few months before her college journey began. After being diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia, he ended his life at the same university where she was entering as a new student. Now Cady is struggling with this missing piece in her life but also with the puzzle of why Eric ended his. She throws herself into this quest to understand her brother's final moments and winds up in a scary situation all of her own. Not long after she arrives at Harvard, Cady begins hearing voices. This all too familiar scenario makes her question if she is destined to end up with the same illness as her brother. But things begin to take a different turn for Cady as she begins to unravel both her story and Eric's story and finds that they are very much intertwined. Cady begins making it her mission to untangle them and what she finds out may cost her everything.Overall, I enjoyed this fast paced and suspenseful first novel from Francesca Serritella. The story flowed well and was hard to put down! There were many twists and turns, some I saw coming, some I did not. I feel she painted a very clear picture of the general pressure that comes with being a college student. She also did a good job showing a grieving family, especially survivors of suicide. I would have liked to have seen some more mental health supports mentioned in the book (i.e. crisis lines, grief counseling, psychoeducation around a serious mental health diagnosis such as schizophrenia). There were some confusing plot points, especially with the ghosts. While they are obviously important to the story, based on the title, I had a hard time taking them seriously. I appreciated the research that went into creating their characters, but I found them out of place with the rest of the story. I wanted them to fit more witt Eric's experience. The other confusing point was related to Eric's condition. I found myself doubting whether the schizophrenia diagnosis was accurate or not. That may be due to the fact I am a mental health professional and kind of a diagnostic nerd! But it did feel slightly confusing at times. Overall, I recommend this book. I think many will find it very interesting and exciting.Thank you to the publisher, Random House, and to NetGalley for this advanced reader copy in exchange for my honest ....more

review: Update: I finished my second reading of Magic Lessons by Alice Hoffman and I can honestly say everything I wrote below still holds true. The first reaUpdate: I finished my second reading of Magic Lessons by Alice Hoffman and I can honestly say everything I wrote below still holds true. The first reading was very intense and I flew through the pages, to the point I didn’t remember all of the story! But this time I was able to relax and savor it, although I still found myself holding my breath from time to time. I caught things I missed and experienced the sights and smells once more. I’m sure I’ll return to it again and again and find new treasures each reading. Alice Hoffman may have just written the very best book ever to be written! If I could give it 10 stars, I would! While I’ve been a Hoffman fan for a long time, I didn’t read Practical Magic until Rules of Magic came out in 2017. Magic Lessons tells the story of how it all began for the Owens family. We first meet Hannah, who gives Maria a home and is her first teacher. We follow Maria through many adventures, including a wonderfully visual trip to Curaçao and then a harrowing journey to Salem, Massachusetts and later to New York. We watch Maria fall in and out of love and experience the joy and pain of motherhood. We experience alongside Maria what it feels to be treated horribly for no reason other than being true to oneself. And above all, we experience Magic like no one else can deliver. Throughout the book, Hoffman tells us her signature story of mothers and daughters and the lengths they go to for one another. She uses the most descriptive imagery for the beautiful flora and fauna along the journey. She writes about teas and cakes and other fantastic concoctions.There were many times reading this that I caught myself holding my breath from anticipation. I literally did not want to stop reading this book. I, almost defiantly, put it down for a day just to make it last a little longer. I cannot stress enough how perfect this book is. I will be pre-ordering so I can read again and again along with the other Owens family stories. Thank you to the publisher and to NetGalley for the advanced copy of the wonderful book....more

She wakes up suddenly and tries to forget. 4 and a half years go by and Dannie still hasn't set a wedding date...life keeps getting in the way. One night she and her fiance meet her best friend, Bella, for dinner on a double date only to find that her best friend's date is the man she dreamed about. All Dannie can think about why he is in her life and more importantly, how she can change the future. Along the way, Dannie has to learn many hard lessons, including accepting the unexpected.Review: Told from Dannie's perspective, this fast paced and heart breaking novel, examines love and one's chosen family. The author uses "the dream" to frame the entire story and I loved the feel and rhythm of this book. It feels suspenseful knowing Dannie is on somewhat of a countdown. This isn't a romance book (believe me, not my thing) but it is a love story. It is a rather short novel, which made it a fast read, but I found myself wanting more. I would have liked to have seen a little more plot development before the story's major twist occurred. But overall, I really enjoyed and would recommend to anyone wanting a heartfelt, yet not sappy, summer read. ...more

The second half is examples of various scary situations (i.e fears of school shootings, house fires, storms, bullying, etc) and sample dialogues between parents and children. Told with “red light” and “green light” examples, parents can see themselves in these responses. I admit it became quite repetitive as the dialogues were slightly formulaic. review: For more s, check out my new blog at www.everydaymamabooks.comSummary: Henna House tells the story of Adela Demaris, a Jewish woman from Yemen. For more s, check out my new blog at www.everydaymamabooks.comSummary: Henna House tells the story of Adela Demaris, a Jewish woman from Yemen. She begins recalling her life as a young child, the only girl in a house of boys. She was born in the 1920s, during the time of the Orphans Decree, which allowed the Arab Inman, also known as “The Confiscator,” to take orphaned Jewish children and adopt them into Muslim families, thereby converting them to their new religion. To protect a young child, it was necessary to betroth at a very young age, some even were betrothed in utero. Adela has pretty bad luck with all of her betrothed and by the age of 8, she was practically an old maid. Finally she is engaged to a cousin she has never met and her family can breathe a sigh of relief. Her cousin becomes a friend and together they plan a future. Even as children, they knew there was more for them than what their little Yemen town had to offer. Their relief is short lived as circumstances change and Adela’s future is no longer secure. But her salvation comes in the form of some estranged extended family that enters their lives, and they brought a new character with them: Henna. As Adela’s story unfolds, she has to learn to navigate the world, which often is unkind, and find her identify. Henna plays an important role and will lead her to many truths along the journey. Review: Adela’s story takes many tragic and joyful turns, all alongside her family and her henna. Told in the first person, the author does an amazing job of weaving important history into a captivating story. I admit I am not very familiar with this part of the world and this book taught me about history, customs, and rituals important to my Jewish brothers and sisters. I highly recommend this book. ...more

review: First there was Elizabeth Bennett and Mr. Darcy. Then Jane Eyre and Mr. Rochester. Then Anne Shirley and Gilbert Blythe. But then came Sarah Prine andFirst there was Elizabeth Bennett and Mr. Darcy. Then Jane Eyre and Mr. Rochester. Then Anne Shirley and Gilbert Blythe. But then came Sarah Prine and Captain Jack Elliot. In this amazing, unforgettable book called These Is My Words, we are introduced to 16 year old Sarah and are taken through 20 years as she navigates life and love in the Wild West. Set in the late 1800s, the author uses diary entries to tell Sarah’s story. I can’t even stress how much I loved this book. I read every spare minute for 5 days. Sarah is a hard working, smart, funny, and loving woman. She is wise and quick on her feet. She loves fiercely and feels deeply. I could identify with Sarah many times as she experienced being a wife and mother. I admire her work ethic and commitment to learning. She is a self taught reader, rancher, and business woman. She knows what to do when a rattlesnake is getting to close to her baby as well as when a rogue cowboy needs to be put in his place. She can handle baking pies, sewing aprons, and averting a train robbery. She is simply the best. This is a different time period and setting than my normal historical fiction choices and I am so glad I read it. The action was addicting and the love story was perfect. Sarah and Jack will forever be one of my favorite literary couples and that is saying something to add them to the list above! I am anxious to read the others in this series! ...more

review: “I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, we need to burn diet culture to the ground.” I think this quote sums us what Christy Harrison aims to do t“I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, we need to burn diet culture to the ground.” I think this quote sums us what Christy Harrison aims to do throughout this book and in her work in the anti-diet space. Ms. Harrison teaches us so much in this important book that it is difficult to summarize in a . We learn about the history of diet culture, and how it has gained attention over the decades. We learn about important concepts such as intuitive eating and Health at Every Size. We learn about the importance of community and social justice around body acceptance and liberation. We learn that health is not a moral obligation and that weight is not a determinant of our health outcomes, as many would have us believe. We learn how to support others and ourselves on this journey to freedom from the chains of The Life Thief (aka diet culture). I highly recommend this book to anyone who has ever questioned why intentional weight loss rarely works or has been stigmatized for their body size or shape. Honestly, it will open your mind and make you mad all at the same time. But then there is a peace that comes where you feel heard and seen. I loved everything about this book, well except the dig at baths :) I appreciated the footnote but I stand firm on my stance as a bubble bath lover :) .Thank you to the publisher and NetGalley for the advanced copy of this wonderful book....more

I love this final quote that sums up this framework. “When you are freed from the tyranny of food and body anxiety, you have the space and renewed energy to pursue your dreams and discover your purpose in life.” If any of that resonates with you, I highly encourage you to read this book. I am grateful to these authors and researchers for this book. Written in 1995 and on its third edition, it is backed by many studies that support Intuitive Eating. Not as a weight loss strategy. She has a wonderful and supportive father and the memory of her mother remains strong in their family. Piper learns many lessons along the way and emerges as a confident and kind young lady.The authors painted a realistic, albeit somewhat cheesy, picture of a single father trying to do his best for his daughter. There are some parts that remind me of Wonder-in good ways. Kids can never hear enough about the importance of kindness and selflessness. review: While I enjoyed this book and feel it deserves a 4 star rating, I have mixed feelings about it. It shows the harsh realities of life for some childrenWhile I enjoyed this book and feel it deserves a 4 star rating, I have mixed feelings about it. It shows the harsh realities of life for some children, I.e domestic violence, hunger, poverty, underfunded schools, etc. On one hand, this can help these children feel understood as they can identify with and see themselves in the characters. It can also raise empathy and understanding for children who are not exposed to the same injustices. On the other hand, I’m not entirely sure all 9-11 year olds could handle this. It takes some emotional intelligence that is not always available at this age, especially for kids who fall into the group of not having experienced this suffering. It deserves conversation though, no matter who reads it. There was a section that I loved. The teacher was reading aloud to the class and the main character said that listening to the story just made her want to dream and not worry anymore. This is a great example of why reading to kids is so important. It gives them an escape through the story but also shows them the love and care of an adult. If you work with kids or families that experience tragedy and suffering, this is a good read for you. Just discuss with kids if they read it. ...more

review: I enjoyed this book very much. It was a good experience for me to get into someone else's lived experience of a very traumatic time. Ana is the exact I enjoyed this book very much. It was a good experience for me to get into someone else's lived experience of a very traumatic time. Ana is the exact same age as me. Both born in 1981. Except when I was 10, I was playing outside with my friends, riding bikes and skating. I had no real worries or cares. When Ana was 10, she watched both of her parents die as casualties on the Croatian civil war. When I was 20, I was in college and watched in horror (yet in safety) as the World Trade Center was attached. Ana was in college too, in New York City. Her experience of this trauma and the ensuing war was vastly different due to her past experience. War in her world meant road side checkpoints and children in combat. review: Oh Anna Karenina. Anna, Anna, Anna. I guess Kostya Levin would not have made for a good title but he was definitely the main (and more tolerable) charOh Anna Karenina. Anna, Anna, Anna. I guess Kostya Levin would not have made for a good title but he was definitely the main (and more tolerable) character. This was my first foray into Tolstoy and I was a little intimidated at first. The writing itself was beautiful. The story was very boring in many ways. The last 25% really picked up and I flew through it in a few days (after taking 7 months to read the first 75%!). It was very spiritual (which I did not expect) and Levin really grew on me and I came to love him in the end. And Anna? I can't even talk about Anna. The phrase "hot mess?" Anna. I'm glad I read it and I will spend some time reflecting on it because there are some thoughtful passages, especially toward the end. Do I recommend? Yes, if you enjoy classics and particularly Russian history. No, if you're only curious. ...more

title: For the Love: Fighting for Grace in a World of Impossible Standards
author: Hatmaker, Jen*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I really wanted to like this book. I like Jen Hatmaker's witty, slightly self deprecating and sarcastic tone on Facebook. The full length book, howeveI really wanted to like this book. I like Jen Hatmaker's witty, slightly self deprecating and sarcastic tone on Facebook. The full length book, however, was just a little much for me. Don't get me wrong, it had its moments where I laughed and was thought provoking at times. I could identify with much of it, being a product of 90's youth group culture and attending an evangelical college and even being married to a pastor. I have had a similar transformation of theology and thought processes regarding the church and Christianity in general. My problem is I felt this book was too "fluffy" and not well developed at all. First, the concept of Grace was not really fleshed out. It was brought up in the beginning and briefly mentioned a few times. This was surprising given the title of the book. Second, the humor. While i enjoyed parts of the more humorous sections, the way they were interspersed between more serious essays made it almost impossible to "sit with" or wrestle with the more difficult topic. One just went from serious to funny and this doesn't leave time for reflection. Also, the humor is reflective of her position as an upper middle class Christian mother of five in the suburbs. Third, many of the community building issues addressed (supper clubs, front porch church, etc) seem like great ideas. For Jen Hatmaker. She obviously has the gift of hospitality. But this doesn't work for everyone. Community can and should be created everywhere. At the gas station pumping gas next to the minivan full of kids or next to the homeless person asking for money. Community can be at the local playground. It doesn't always involve opening ones home and cooking. Close knit "Couple friends" may be necessary for her but they aren't for me. Lastly, Jen's writing seems to be more like journal entries of her own thoughts and reflections on other authors' writings. I didn't see much I hadn't already heard before. Also, She definitely wrote to her specific audience and if one isn't married with children, it may be difficult to relate to much of the content. ...more

title: Still Alice
author: Genova, Lisa*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: 2017 update. I listened to this book as my second reading and all my feelings remained pretty much the same. Her husband disappointed me but it may al2017 update. I listened to this book as my second reading and all my feelings remained pretty much the same. Her husband disappointed me but it may also be a realistic picture of what happens. The writing is truly amazing. I love how even the narration changes are Alice’s disease progresses. It still makes me want to change careers to cognitive psychology. I highly recommend this as well as all of Lisa Genova’s books. This book was both fascinating and heart breaking at the same time. Although I don't have any direct experience with Alzheimer's Disease, especially early onset, I have always been very interested in it. When I was back in college taking psychology classes, I even considered furthering my studies in cognitive psych to study Alzheimer's. Still Alice was an intelligent and well written first person account of this disease and the toll it takes on both the person and the family. Written from the perspective of Alice, a brilliant neuro psychologist, makes the irony of losing her memory very strong. I loved how her children all responded and changed with her diagnosis and the fast progression of her illness. Her husband's responses would make me cry on one page and then make me mad the next page. But it seemed to be a realistic picture of how a family may react in this situation. The author holds a PhD in neuroscience herself, and while the novel is very factual, it doesn't read like a textbook in any way. So, yes, 5 stars for Still Alice. Read this if you are even remotely interested or know someone with this horrible and heartbreaking disease....more

review: Claire finished 11/27/16Over the last 6 months, I have read all the Harry Potter books for the first time. I never saw the movies (well I did see the Claire finished 11/27/16Over the last 6 months, I have read all the Harry Potter books for the first time. I never saw the movies (well I did see the first movie when it was in the theater but I fell asleep) and I had always written them off as "not my genre." But over the last several years, I began challenging myself to expand my horizons and I have picked a different genre each year to focus on. This year was fantasy and the Harry Potter books were a wonderful choice to begin. And since I have been under a rock apparently, I knew nothing of the story and was able to discover it as I went, which was really fun. Each book grew on me more and more and I can honestly say I loved them all. But this last one was such an amazing ending to this series. I feel Rowling really tied up many loose ends and gave closure to her characters, which with the massive following was probably necessary. It had sweet moments, funny moments, scary moments, sad moments and cry my eyes out moments. I wish I could pick one character or story line I loved the most but its so hard to narrow down. So here is my top 10 to round out my  on this series.10. Dobby and Kreacher. I love the continued story with the elves and of course Ron's concern to free all the elves at Hogwarts and Hermoine's response made my laugh and cry. 9. Mrs. Weasley's confrontation of Bellatrix. Wow, that is one good red headed mama.8. Luna. She cracks me up.7. The Malfoys. Redemption!6. The fact that these kids go through 7 years of school and all these adventures and don't ever use a phone or a computer. I know those are Muggle inventions and all but it was refreshing!5. Dudley! He's growing up!4. SNAPE! Oh my! I love the concept of the Penseive (wish I had one!) and I was glad to see it used in such a powerful way here.3. Dumbledore. I heart him. But it was good to get a different view, he wasn't perfect and he knew it. 2. Ron/Hermoine. Best friends turned into true love is always the way to go. They had to suffer alone and come back together enough to know it is real.1. Harry of course. The Epilogue. Everything. I'm a little sad that it's over. And if you read this whole thing, you now know the true level of my nerdiness....more

The love story is powerful but the friendship that exists among this group of teenagers is also rare-the kind of friends I would want to have if I ever found myself in this horrible situation. I also have to add how its funny how things converge in life. I JUST finished the Anne Frank's diary and here it is playing a pretty significant role in this book. review: This book was amazing. I love how he sees the world and copes with his mental illness. This was a realistic view of family and the lengths we go to foThis book was amazing. I love how he sees the world and copes with his mental illness. This was a realistic view of family and the lengths we go to for those we love. Every character in this book touched me in some way and I just want to sit down with all of them (yes, I know they aren't real!!). I know it is a good book when I keep thinking of the characters after its over and I am certainly doing that now. 1/22/2016-I listened to the audio version of SLP this week and all of my feelings were the same, if not better, for this book. This time, I really saw how similar Pat was to his father and brother. The reality is, his dad and brother have a lot of the same mental health issues but Pat went too far which required a change in his life. I really think he is better off than his dad in a lot of ways. And the idea of "being kind rather than right" just makes good sense! I love the author's way with words and how he uses repetition in just the right way. The "montage" is my favorite part, along with the dance competition. All in all, an excellent book about love and families. This will definitely be one I return to every few years. ...more

review: Today I finished Les Misérables. I set out to read it over 2016 and I brought it in just in time. 1200 pages! I really could write an entire book repoToday I finished Les Misérables. I set out to read it over 2016 and I brought it in just in time. 1200 pages! I really could write an entire book report on this incredible work. It is hard to even write a . Les Misérables will go down as the most unique book I have ever read. It was a mixture of fiction, history, theology, and politics, all rolled into one. Hugo wrote some beautiful words and is King of the "mic drop." This man knows how to end a paragraph! This was one of those books that has made me a better person and I'll be forever changed and moved by it. I will just leave a few quotes that were important to me and spoke to me throughout the pages. ---"His (the Bishop) universal goodwill was not so much a natural inclination as a firm conviction that had trickled into his heart from life, slowly dripping into him, thought by thought; for a person's nature, like a rock, can be drilled into by drops of water. Such channels bored through are ineffaceable, such formations, indestructible."---"The most beautiful of altars," he said, "is the soul of an unhappy creature consoled and thanking God."---"Marius and Cosette never asked themselves whither this was to lead them. They considered that they had already arrived. It is a strange claim on man's part to wish that love should lead to something."---"And by the way, Monsieur Marius, I (Eponine) believe that I was a little bit in love with you."---"All the light of his life had departed, while he still fancied that he beheld the sun."---"The pupil dilates in the dark, and the soul dilates in misfortune and ends by finding God there."---"He is there on high, he sees us all, and he knows what he does in the midst of his great stars."And finally:---"Love each other well and always. There is nothing else but that in the world: love for each other."...more

review: This book is a hidden treasure. Coming at the end of the Anne of Green Gables series, it tells the story of Rilla, Anne's youngest child. It is set duThis book is a hidden treasure. Coming at the end of the Anne of Green Gables series, it tells the story of Rilla, Anne's youngest child. It is set during WWI, and tells the story from the perspective of Rilla and the rest of the family who are at home in Canada while many of their boys go off to the front lines. Rilla is forced to grow up during this time and leave her silly girlish ways behind. Rilla is a different character than Anne. She is rather whimsical and can wax poetic like her mother but she lacks ambition-something that changes as she grows. Rilla is just as loveable and I was constantly rooting for her. L M Montgomery is a true story teller. I felt like I was at Ingleside with the family as I read this book. Laughter and tears were common and the ending is just perfect. Even if you haven't read the other books, read this one. ...more
